04253nam a22006135i 9780300132007DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001320077 a10.12987/97803001320072doi  a(DE-B1597)485309  a(OCoLC)1013936059  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aJF2071b.G74 2002eb 7aPOL0150002bisacsh04a306.2/6/09732211 aGreen, Donald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPartisan Hearts and Minds :bPolitical Parties and the Social Identities of Voters /cDonald Green, Eric Schickler, Bradley Palmquist. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b14 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Institution for Social and Policy Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Partisan Groups as Objects of Identification -- tChapter 3. A Closer Look at Partisan Stability -- tChapter 4. Partisan Stability: Evidence from Aggregate Data -- tChapter 5. Partisan Stability and Voter Learning -- tChapter 6. Party Realignment in the American South -- tChapter 7. Partisan Stability outside the United States -- tChapter 8. How Partisan Attachments Structure Politics -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this, the first major treatment of party identification in twenty years, three political scientists assert that identification with political parties still powerfully determines how citizens look at politics and cast their ballots. Challenging prevailing views, they build a case for the continuing theoretical and political significance of partisan identities.The authors maintain that individuals form partisan attachments early in adulthood and that these political identities, much like religious identities, tend to persist or change only slowly over time. Scandals, recessions, and landslide elections do not greatly affect party identification; large shifts in party attachments occur only when the social imagery of a party changes, as when African Americans became part of the Democratic Party in the South after the passage of the Voting Rights Act. Drawing on a wealth of data analysis using individual-level and aggregate survey data from the United States and abroad, this study offers a new perspective on party identification that will set the terms of discussion for years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aParty affiliationxUnited States. 0aParty affiliationzUnited States. 0aParty affiliation. 0aVotingxUnited States. 0aVotingzUnited States. 0aVoting. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Parties.2bisacsh1 aPalmquist, Bradley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSchickler, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300132007423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300132007.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles